Let's say you have a calculator module. Instead of tightly coupling the logic with printing or error handling, design it as follows:

```rust
// traits.rs
pub trait Calculator {
    fn add(&self, a: i32, b: i32) -> i32;
}
```
Then create an implementation without side effects:

```rust
// calculator.rs
use crate::traits::Calculator;

pub struct SimpleCalculator;
impl Calculator for SimpleCalculator {
    fn add(&self, a: i32, b: i32) -> i32 {
        a + b
    }
}
```
Finally, use it in your main logic:

```rust
// main.rs
mod traits;
mod calculator;

use calculator::SimpleCalculator;
use traits::Calculator;

fn main() {
    let calc: Box<dyn Calculator> = Box::new(SimpleCalculator);
    let result = calc.add(3, 5);
    println!("Result: {}");
}
```
This way, you can easily swap out the calculator implementation later, demonstrating inversion and composability.

Yes—centralize error handling where possible for maintainability, but design your modules with clear error boundaries. Use `Result` extensively; you can then bubble up or recover gracefully:

```rust
fn calculate_and_print() -> Result<(), String> {
    let calc: Box<dyn Calculator> = Box::new(SimpleCalculator);
    let result = calc.add(3, 5);
